    "content": "**AI & Robotics Snacks** — April 4, 2026\n\n---\n\n## 🖥️ GPT-5.4 Is Better Than a Human at Using a Computer. That Happened.\n\nOpenAI's GPT-5.4, released in early March, just crossed a line: **75.0%** on OSWorld-Verified, the benchmark for AI desktop navigation. Human expert baseline: 72.4%. First time any model has beaten humans at operating a computer through screenshots and mouse clicks.\n\n- **What that benchmark measures:** clicking through apps, filling forms, orchestrating tasks across desktop software — no direct code access. It measures exactly what most knowledge workers do for 3–4 hours a day.\n- **The computer use pivot:** GPT-5.4 ships with a native computer use mode. Point it at any enterprise software. The question is no longer \"can it?\" — it's \"why aren't you already doing this?\"\n\n*A model that's better than you at operating your own computer. Very normal development.*\n\n**Sources:** [OpenAI](https://openai.com/index/introducing-gpt-5-4/) | [TechCrunch](https://techcrunch.com/2026/03/05/openai-launches-gpt-5-4-with-pro-and-thinking-versions/)\n\n---\n\n## 💼 Oracle Is Laying Off Up to 30,000 People (AI Investment Doing Great, Thanks)\n\nOracle announced sweeping layoffs in April — estimates put the number at up to 30,000 — while simultaneously increasing AI infrastructure spending. Official rationale varies by division. Unofficial rationale is in the CEO's AI strategy deck.\n\n- **The sector context:** 52,000 tech job cuts in Q1 2026 alone — the highest first-quarter total since 2023. Meta, Google, Amazon, Salesforce, Atlassian all cut while explicitly citing AI productivity gains.\n- **The gap:** a Fortune survey found CFOs privately expect AI-attributed layoffs to run **9x higher** than publicly disclosed figures. \"Workforce realignment\" is doing a lot of rhetorical heavy lifting right now.\n\n*Oracle is investing in AI and cutting 30,000 jobs simultaneously. That's not a bug in the strategy.*\n\n**Sources:** [Bloomberg](https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2026-04-02/us-job-cut-announcements-in-tech-keep-rising-with-ai-adoption) | [Fortune](https://fortune.com/2026/03/24/cfo-survey-ai-job-cuts-productivity-paradox-2026/)\n\n---\n\n## ⏱️ AI Saves Workers 60 Minutes a Day — 80% of Companies Aren't Using It Yet\n\nGoldman Sachs research: enterprise AI users save 40–60 minutes per day, 75% say they can complete tasks they previously couldn't do at all. Meanwhile, 80% of companies haven't reached meaningful adoption. The math on that gap is uncomfortable.\n\n- **The budget paradox:** 86% of companies plan to increase AI spending in 2026. Only 64% are actually using AI in operations. Most are funding infrastructure they're not yet running.\n- **The compounding window:** early adopters have a measurable, widening advantage. Late movers are financing their own irrelevance while competitors move faster with the same tools.\n\n*60 minutes per worker per day. 80% of companies still on the sideline. The clock is running — not at the same rate for everyone.*\n\n**Sources:** [Fortune](https://fortune.com/2026/04/01/ai-worker-productivity-adoption-goldman-sachs-saves-60-minutes-per-day/) | [NVIDIA Blog](https://blogs.nvidia.com/blog/state-of-ai-report-2026/)"
